      <h1>How to Calculate Overtime Pay Under FLSA Rules</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>Jun 18, 2026</span><span>·</span><span>5 min read</span></div>
      <p class="article-intro">Understanding how overtime is calculated is essential for ensuring you are paid fairly. Here is the step-by-step guide to calculating overtime pay under the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA).</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container" style="max-width:740px;">
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="callout"><strong>The basic rule:</strong> Under the FLSA, non-exempt employees must receive overtime pay for hours worked over 40 in a workweek at a rate not less than 1.5 times their regular rate of pay.</div>

      <h2>What is the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA)?</h2>
      <p>The FLSA is a federal US law that establishes minimum wage, overtime pay eligibility, recordkeeping, and youth employment standards. It applies to both full-time and part-time workers in the private sector and in federal, state, and local governments.</p>

      <h2>Who is eligible for overtime pay?</h2>
      <p>Workers are divided into two main categories under the FLSA:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Non-Exempt Employees:</strong> These workers are entitled to overtime pay. Most hourly workers are non-exempt, though salaried employees earning below a certain salary threshold can also qualify as non-exempt.</li>
        <li><strong>Exempt Employees:</strong> These workers are not entitled to overtime pay. To be exempt, an employee must earn above the federal salary threshold and perform specific professional, administrative, or executive duties as defined by the IRS and Department of Labor.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How to calculate overtime pay: Step-by-step</h2>
      <p>Calculating overtime requires finding your "regular rate of pay" and multiplying hours worked beyond 40 by 1.5 times that rate.</p>

      <h3>Step 1: Determine the regular hourly rate</h3>
      <p>For standard hourly workers, this is your basic hourly wage. If you earn $20 per hour, your regular rate is $20. If you receive bonuses or commissions, these must be factored in to determine your "regular rate" for that workweek.</p>

      <h3>Step 2: Calculate the overtime rate (Time-and-a-half)</h3>
      <p>Multiply the regular rate of pay by 1.5:</p>
      <pre><code>Overtime rate = Regular rate × 1.5
$20/hr × 1.5 = $30/hour</code></pre>

      <h3>Step 3: Calculate total earnings</h3>
      <p>If you work 48 hours in a workweek, your earnings are split into 40 regular hours and 8 overtime hours:</p>
      <pre><code>Regular earnings:  40 hours × $20 = $800
Overtime earnings: 8 hours × $30 = $240
Total gross pay:   $800 + $240 = $1,040</code></pre>

      <h2>Important FLSA overtime details</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Workweek Standard:</strong> Overtime is calculated on a single workweek basis (7 consecutive 24-hour periods). You cannot average hours over two weeks. E.g., working 30 hours in week 1 and 50 hours in week 2 requires paying 10 hours of overtime in week 2.</li>
        <li><strong>No Limit on Hours:</strong> The FLSA does not limit the number of hours an employee (aged 16 or older) can work in a workweek; it only requires paying overtime for hours over 40.</li>
        <li><strong>State Laws:</strong> Some states have stricter overtime rules. For example, California requires paying overtime (1.5x) for hours worked over 8 in a single day, and double-time (2x) for hours worked over 12 in a single day.</li>
      </ul>
